node.text:
Explorer/Activist Johan Ernst Nilson. Nilson has climbed the Seven Summits (and many other peaks), visited 178 countries and some of the most remote places on Earth, and he is in the Guinness Book of World Records for his Three Poles Challenge Expedition. His travels and experiences have allowed him to see climate change and its consequences first hand, and now Nilson is an activist for change, leading people on expeditions, giving talks, and making films about the environment.

node.text:
The Astronomia Everest project started with renowned Swedish explorer and environmental activist @johanernst taking an Astronomia Tourbillon with him on an expedition to the Himalayas.
"I wore the regular Astronomia Tourbillon on my last climb to the Himalayas, where I went up to 6,200 meters (almost 20,000 feet), in -30 C degree, extreme conditions," Nilson says. "You would think that such a complicated watch would be delicate and fragile, but it isn't, and it performed perfectly in all conditions. I used it climbing up ice walls, with my ice ax, banging it against rock and ice and it held up extremely well.”

Explorer/Activist Johan Ernst Nilson. Nilson has climbed the Seven Summits (and many other peaks), visited 178 countries and some of the most remote places on Earth, and he is in the Guinness Book of World Records for his Three Poles Challenge Expedition. His travels and experiences have allowed him to see climate change and its consequences first hand, and now Nilson is an activist for change, leading people on expeditions, giving talks, and making films about the environment.

node.text:
Push the right-hand crown of the incredible BUGATTI Chiron Tourbillon and the engine comes to life – the crankshaft turns and the 16 pistons pump up and down, just like BUGATTI’S iconic W16 engine. Two “turbochargers” on the side of the engine block spin while the engine runs, adding to the visual impact.
Incredible to see and unbelievably complicated to realize (the movement is comprised of 578 components), the BUGATTI Chiron Tourbillon timepiece seamlessly marries engines and watches – something no other watchmaker has done before.

The Astronomia Everest project started with renowned Swedish explorer and environmental activist @johanernst taking an Astronomia Tourbillon with him on an expedition to the Himalayas.
"I wore the regular Astronomia Tourbillon on my last climb to the Himalayas, where I went up to 6,200 meters (almost 20,000 feet), in -30 C degree, extreme conditions," Nilson says. "You would think that such a complicated watch would be delicate and fragile, but it isn't, and it performed perfectly in all conditions. I used it climbing up ice walls, with my ice ax, banging it against rock and ice and it held up extremely well.”

Explorer/Activist Johan Ernst Nilson. Nilson has climbed the Seven Summits (and many other peaks), visited 178 countries and some of the most remote places on Earth, and he is in the Guinness Book of World Records for his Three Poles Challenge Expedition. His travels and experiences have allowed him to see climate change and its consequences first hand, and now Nilson is an activist for change, leading people on expeditions, giving talks, and making films about the environment.

In the world of watchmaking, the presence of a tourbillon in a watch’s movement places the piece among the elite. @JacobandCo’s Twin Turbo Furious 300+ sets itself apart from this rarified group, incorporating two accelerated triple axis tourbillons into its striking design. The tourbillons work to compensate for the effects of gravity on the precision of the movement.⠀ ⠀
⠀
Even the case of the Twin Turbo Furious Bugatti 300+ is super complicated – made of forged carbon, with a titanium core to ensure water resistance - the case alone is comprised of 88 parts. The grand complication movement is made up of 832 individual parts – incredible to consider that many parts coming together, and amazing to see in action.⠀

Titanium is one of the lightest and strongest metals in the world. In addition, its natural silver color can be transformed by heat or electric current into a spectrum of different shades.

The metallic blue color of the Jacob & Co. node.text:
Inside the case of the Bugatti Chiron Tourbillon Rose Gold is a replica of the Bugatti 16-cylinder engine clearly visible through tinted sapphire crystal, specially designed to simulate tinted car windows of a Bugatti Chiron. The sapphire crystal provides a full view of the engine, suspended within the watch case by four pillars that look like Chiron shock absorbers.

Activated on demand, the “engine” comes to life with 16 pistons pumping and two turbochargers spinning. In addition, there’s a 30-degree inclined 60-second flying tourbillon visible through the horseshoe-shaped Bugatti grille on the front of the case.

node.text:
The transparent case of the Bugatti Chiron Sapphire Crystal provides an unparalleled view of the fully functional replica of the Bugatti W16 engine with its pistons pumping and two turbochargers spinning. This clarity is the result of hand polishing, which is the final task of a long and complex process that took upwards of 120 hours to complete. This same delicate hand polishing is used for the caseback, the top, the three crowns and other pieces that are attached to the case. Every shape of every piece has a different polishing process. The angles to polish the exteriors and interiors of the case are different. But the quality, including the transparency, must be consistent throughout.

Shaping a block of rough synthetic sapphire into the case of the Bugatti Chiron Sapphire Crystal combines computer-aided design and manufacturing processes and hand polishing. It’s a challenging endeavor that takes several months. The tonneau-shaped Chiron case isn’t a singular exterior but is a mix of geometric surfaces. Then there’s the hardness of sapphire. It measures 9 on the Mohs scale of hardness. Very few materials are harder, including diamond, which measures a 10. Because of this, diamond cutting and polishing tools are used to craft the case. This is both costly and time consuming, but it’s absolutely necessary to produce a case with the exact dimensions and transparency that the Chiron exhibits.

The Astronomia Everest, a watch created by Jacob & Co. in collaboration with Swedish explorer Johan Ernst Nilson, was among 25 artworks, experiences and luxury products that were auctioned off at the recently held LUISAVIAROMA for UNICEF Gala fundraiser in Capri.

Within the iconic Astronomia movement are details that symbolize significant moments from Nilson’s 27 years of adventures, including a rock from Mount Everest mounted on the top of the movement and two glass containers of water collected by Nilson from the North and South Poles to raise awareness of the many environmental issues facing the planet.

The LUISAVIAROMA for UNICEF Gala fundraiser held July 31 in Capri raised more than €5 million ($5.9 million) to support UNICEF’s mission of providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. Among the items sold at a special charity auction was the Astronomia Everest, a watch created in collaboration with Swedish explorer Johan Ernst Nilson, who attended the star-studded event with Jacob Arabo.

“It was a magical night beneath the stars and among the stars but the greatest pleasure of all was being able to support UNICEF and its mission of providing aid to children throughout the world,” Jacob said.

Inside the 47mm black gold and sapphire crystal case of the Astronomia Everest is the iconic Astronomia four-arm vertical movement with its four exclusive complications along with objects from the personal journeys of Swedish explorer, Johan Ernst Nilson, who designed the watch with Jacob Arabo. 

Beneath this spectacular display is a luminous backdrop of the constellations of the Northern Hemisphere on a black titanium base. This watch was one of the items sold in a charity fundraiser in Capri, Italy, to benefit UNICEF and its mission of providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide.
